Response:
The most common symptoms of tuberculosis are fever, night sweats, weight loss and fatigue. These can also be present in other diseases which may be confused for tuberculosis.

Response:
Tuberculosis (TB) is caused by the bacteria Mycobacterium Tuberculosis. It mainly affects the lungs, but it can spread to any part of the body through the bloodstream. The symptoms are usually mild and nonspecific. These include fever, night sweats, weight loss, fatigue, anorexia, abdominal pain (with peritoneal TB), chest pains (with pleural effusion) or a persistent cough with blood in the sputum (suggestive of pulmonary Tb).

